+{"role":"user","message":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"<user_query>\ncan you do subagents?\n</user_query>"}]}}
+{"role":"assistant","message":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Yes. I can spin off **subagents** (via the Task tool) when a job is a good fit for parallel or delegated work—for example:\n\n- **explore** — quickly map the codebase, find files, answer “where does X live?”\n- **generalPurpose** — multi-step research or implementation in isolation\n- **shell** — command-focused work (git, builds, scripts)\n- **best-of-n-runner** — isolated attempts in separate worktrees\n\nI don’t use them for tiny, one-shot questions or when a single direct search/read is enough; I use them when splitting work actually saves time or keeps context cleaner. If you tell me what you want done, I can say whether a subagent helps and which type fits."}]}}
+{"role":"user","message":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"<user_query>\nare you capable of running an agent loop? can you spawn a subagent that will begin working it's way down the plan.md list and occasionally checking in to see how it's doing or restart it if needed?\n</user_query>"}]}}
+{"role":"assistant","message":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here’s an accurate picture of what’s possible.\n\n### Agent loop (me in this chat)\n\nYes, in a limited sense. I can repeat **plan → use tools → read results → adjust → repeat** for many turns in one conversation. That’s the usual “agent loop” here. It isn’t a background daemon: it stops when the session ends or you stop replying, and there are practical limits on how long a single run can go.\n\n### Subagent that “works down `plan.md` and checks in / restarts itself”\n\n**Not as a single autonomous long-running process.** A spawned subagent is generally **one shot**: it gets a task, runs until it finishes (or hits its own limits), then returns a result to me. It doesn’t sit in a loop polling you or “restarting itself” like a supervisor unless **I** (or you) drive that from the parent side.\n\nWhat *does* work well:\n\n- **I act as the loop**: I read `plan.md`, delegate a **chunk** (e.g. one section or N items) to a subagent, review the outcome, then either delegate the next chunk or call again with a **resume** / follow-up prompt if the tooling supports it. “Restart if needed” = I detect failure or drift and issue a new task with clearer constraints.\n- **You act as the loop**: you say “continue from item 7” and I resume orchestration.\n\nSo: **orchestrated multi-step execution across `plan.md` — yes; one subagent silently self-managing and checking in with you over time — not really; that’s better modeled as me (or you) running repeated subagent calls.**\n\nIf you want this for your repo, the next step is to point me at `plan.md` (or its path) and say whether you prefer **one item per subagent** vs **batches**, and I can outline a concrete workflow that matches how your plan is structured."}]}}
